SIMPLE: mount
RECORDS: 4

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Mount
<hw>Mount</hw> <pr>(mount)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[OE.
<ets>munt</ets>, <ets>mont</ets>, <ets>mount</ets>, AS. <ets>munt</ets>,
fr. L. <ets>mons</ets>, <ets>montis</ets>; cf. L. <ets>minae</ets>
protections, E. <ets>eminent</ets>, <ets>menace</ets>: cf. F.
<ets>mont</ets>. Cf. <er>Mount</er>, <pos>v.</pos>, <er>Mountain</er>,
<er>Mont</er>, <er>Monte</er>, <er>Montem</er>.]</ety> <sn>1.</sn>
<def>A mass of earth, or earth and rock, rising considerably above the
common surface of the surrounding land; a mountain; a high hill; -- used
always instead of <xex>mountain</xex>, when put before a proper name;
<as>as, <ex>Mount</ex> Washington</as>; otherwise, chiefly in
poetry.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A bulwark for offense or defense; a mound.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Hew ye down trees, and cast a <qex>mount</qex> against
Jerusalem.</q> <rj><qau>Jer. vi. 6.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <ety>[See <er>Mont de pi⟦eacute⟧t⟦eacute⟧</er>.]</ety>
<def>A bank; a fund.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <fld>(Palmistry)</fld> <def>Any one of seven fleshy
prominences in the palm of the hand which are taken as significant of
the influence of ⟦ldquo⟧planets,⟦rdquo⟧ and called the <xex>mounts</xex>
of Jupiter, Mars, Mercury, the Moon, Saturn, the Sun or Apollo, and
Venus.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>Webster 1913 Suppl.</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>Mount of piety</b></col>. <cd>See <er>Mont de
pi⟦eacute⟧t⟦eacute⟧</er>.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mount</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Mount
<hw>Mount</hw>, <pos>v. i.</pos> <vmorph>[<pos>imp. & p. p.</pos>
<conjf>Mounted</conjf> <pr>(?)</pr>; <pos>p. pr. & vb. n.</pos>
<conjf>Mounting</conjf>.]</vmorph> <ety>[OE. <ets>mounten</ets>,
<ets>monten</ets>, F. <ets>monter</ets>, fr. L. <ets>mons</ets>,
<ets>montis</ets>, mountain. See <er>Mount</er>, <pos>n.</pos>
(above).]</ety> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To rise on high; to go up; to be
upraised or uplifted; to tower aloft; to ascend; -- often with
<xex>up</xex>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Though Babylon should <qex>mount</qex> up to heaven.</q>
<rj><qau>Jer. li. 53.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>The fire of trees and houses <qex>mounts</qex> on high.</q>
<rj><qau>Cowley.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To get up on anything, as a platform or scaffold;
especially, to seat one's self on a horse for riding.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To attain in value; to amount.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Bring then these blessings to a strict account,⟦br⟧
Make fair deductions, see to what they <qex>mount</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Pope.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mount</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 3 ====
HEADWORD: Mount
<hw>Mount</hw>, <pos>v. t.</pos> <sn>1.</sn> <def>To get upon; to
ascend; to climb; <as>as, to <ex>mount</ex> the pulpit and deliver a
sermon</as>.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>Shall we <qex>mount</qex> again the rural throne?</q>
<rj><qau>Dryden.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>To place one's self on, as a horse or other animal,
or anything that one sits upon; to bestride.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>3.</sn> <def>To cause to mount; to put on horseback; to furnish
with animals for riding; to furnish with horses.</def> ⟦ldquo⟧To
<xex>mount</xex> the Trojan troop.⟦rdquo⟧ <rj><au>Dryden.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>4.</sn> <def>Hence: To put upon anything that sustains and fits
for use, as a gun on a carriage, a map or picture on cloth or paper; to
prepare for being worn or otherwise used, as a diamond by setting, or a
sword blade by adding the hilt, scabbard, etc.; <as>as, to
<ex>mount</ex> a picture or diploma in a frame</as></def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>5.</sn> <def>To raise aloft; to lift on high.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>What power is it which <qex>mounts</qex> my love so high?</q>
<rj><qau>Shak.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><note>⟦hand⟧ A fort or ship is said to <xex>mount</xex> cannon, when
it has them arranged for use in or about it.</note>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><cs><col><b>To mount guard</b></col> <fld>(Mil.)</fld>, <cd>to go on
guard; to march on guard; to do duty as a guard.</cd> -- <col><b>To
mount a play</b></col>, <cd>to prepare and arrange the scenery,
furniture, etc., used in the play.</cd></cs>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mount</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 4 ====
HEADWORD: Mount
<hw>Mount</hw>, <pos>n.</pos> <ety>[From <er>Mount</er>,
<pos>v.</pos>]</ety> <def>That upon which a person or thing is
mounted</def>, <specif>especially:</specif> <sd>(a)</sd> <def>A
horse.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>She had so good a seat and hand, she might be trusted with any
<qex>mount</qex>.</q> <rj><qau>G. Eliot.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sd>(b)</sd> <def>The cardboard or cloth on which a drawing,
photograph, or the like is mounted; a mounting.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Mountable</ent>⟦br⟧
